FIRST AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS FIRST AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (Agreement) is made and entered into this May 23, 2025 (the Effective Date), by and between Paulding Wind Farm III LLC (Timber Road III), Paulding Wind Farm IV LLC (Timber Road IV), Timber Road Solar Park III LLC (Timber Road III Solar), and Timber Road III Storage LLC (Timber Road III Storage), each of which is a Delaware limited liability company. The foregoing are sometimes referred to herein individually as a Co-Owner and collectively as Co-Owners.
RECITALS
A. The Co-Owners and its Affiliates are developing and have developed wind, solar, and battery energy storage electric generating facilities located on real property in Paulding County, Ohio (the Facilities).
B. The installed nameplate generating capacity of the Facilities (each of which is referred to herein as a Facility and collectively as the Facilities), will be approximately:
Timber Road III Facility: 100.8 MW Timber Road IV Facility: 126 MW Timber Road III Solar Facility: 49.9 MW Timber Road III Storage Facility: 50 MW
C. The Co-Owners wish to own or will own undivided interests in certain real and personal property acquired or to be acquired for their respective Facilities and wish to further share the use and cost of certain electrical transmission, communications¸ structures and other facilities and associated real property rights, and to engage the Operator to operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the recitals, the premises, covenants and conditions contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which the Co- Owners acknowledge, the Co-Owners agree as follows:
ARTICLE I -- DEFINITIONS, INTERPRETATIONS AND EXHIBITS
1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Exhibit A.
1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Persons successors and assigns but, in the case of a Co-Owner, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Law means such Law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in 3 Docusign Envelope ID: 988EE8BB-EF10-4F66-9234-03A65094CA0E
whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) hereunder, hereof, hereto and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) including means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, from means from and including, to means to be excluding and through means through and including.
1.3 Incorporation of Recitals and Exhibits. The Recitals set forth in this Agreement and the Exhibits attached hereto are incorporated into this Agreement by reference for all purposes.
ARTICLE II -- TERM OF AGREEMENT
2.1 Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the Effective Date and shall remain in force and effect until the earlier of (a) the date that is sixty (60) years after the Effective Date, and (b) the retirement and final disposition of all components of the Shared Facilities.
2.2 Payments on Termination. Upon termination of this Agreement, each Co-Owner shall pay Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest at the time of such termination as set forth herein this Agreement, of any remaining balance owed for Operators costs incurred or irrevocably committed to be incurred pursuant to this Agreement as of the date of termination, within sixty (60) days following receipt of an invoice from Operator requiring such payment; provided that Operator shall use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize such costs.
2.3 Survival. Any obligations of one Co-Owner to another, including payment obligations and indemnity obligations, as a result of this Agreement which accrued prior to or as a result of termination of this Agreement shall survive termination of this Agreement.
ARTICLE III -- SHARED FACILITIES AND REAL PROPERTY
3.1 Shared Facilities. The Co-Owners plan to procure, install and construct, or have procured, installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, communications¸ structures and other facilities, as described in Exhibit B, which may be altered or reconstructed by amendment in accordance with this Agreement, for shared use by the Co-Owners (collectively, the Shared Facilities). Each grouping of Shared Facilities is described in Exhibit B (each a Shared Facilities Group).
3.2 Shared Real Property. The Shared Facilities in each Shared Facilities Group are or will be located on certain real property (collectively, the Shared Real Property) that is subject to the easement, lease, option or other rights and obligations in the documents described under the applicable section of Exhibit B (collectively, the Shared Real Property Agreements).
3.3 Shared Assets Groups. Each Shared Facilities Group, combined with the Shared Real Property corresponding to the Shared Facilities in such Shared Facilities Group (Shared Assets) described under the same section in Exhibit B shall be referred to herein as a Shared Assets Group.

3.4 Access. Each Co-Owner shall have a non-exclusive right of access (a) to the Shared Facilities in which it has an Undivided Use Interest as necessary in order to ensure that Operator is meeting its obligations with respect to the operation, maintenance and repair of such Shared Facilities, that Co-Owners Facility remains operational, and for the purposes contemplated in Article VII; and (b) over any Shared Real Property in which such Co-Owner has an Ownership Interest; provided that, subject to the provisions of Section 13.2, if such Co-Owner is not the Operator, it shall (i) provide reasonable notice to Operator, and (ii) not unreasonably interfere with Operators operation, maintenance or repair of the Shared Facilities or of another Co-Owners Facility.
ARTICLE IV -- OWNERSHIP OF AND RIGHT TO USE SHARED ASSETS
4.1 Undivided Ownership Interests. Each Co-Owner owns, or shall own, in accordance with this Agreement, an undivided interest, as a tenant-in-common, in the applicable Shared Assets Group (and equal to its Proportionate Share as set forth and described in Exhibit C in such applicable Shared Assets Group (such undivided interest of each Co-Owner being referred to in this Agreement as its Ownership Interest).
4.1.1 Notice to Acquire. In the event a Co-Owner desires to proceed with the continued development and construction of a Connecting Facility, as defined in Section 4.5 herein, and so long as the conditions precedent set forth in Section 4.2.3 have been satisfied, the Co-Owner shall, at its sole discretion, send a written notice to the Operator and other Co-Owners stating its desire to proceed with the consummation of the Ownership Interest Acquisition (defined below) (the Notice to Acquire).
4.1.2 Ownership Interest Acquisition. Following the receipt of the Notice to Acquire, as soon as reasonably practical, but in any event no earlier than six (6) months prior to the projected commencement of commercial operation by a Connecting Facility, the Co-Owners shall, subject to the satisfaction of Section 4.2.3 and the written consent of each of the Co-Owners, (a)(i) execute the Bill of Sale and (ii) execute the Real Property Assignment and Assumption Agreement and, if applicable the Special Warranty Deed, in each case, pursuant to which the applicable Co-Owner shall own its Ownership Interest, and (b) amend this Agreement as reasonably required to accurately reflect each Co-Owners ownership in the Shared Facilities after giving effect to such acquisition (the Ownership Interest Acquisition). For the avoidance of doubt, Timber Road III and Timber Road IV acquired their Ownership Interest prior to the Effective Date of this First Amended and Restated Shared Facilities Agreement and are not subject to Sections 4.1.1, 4.1.2, 4.2.3, or Section 9.9 herein.
4.2 Undivided Use Interests. Each Co-Owner who has an Ownership Interest in a Shared Assets Group shall have an undivided right to the use or capacity of the applicable Shared Assets equal to its Proportionate Share therein, which right is effective on and after the date that all conditions precedent set forth in Section 4.2.3 applicable to a such Co-Owner (if any) are satisfied (the CP Satisfaction Date) (once exercised, such undivided use interest of a Co-Owner is referred to in this Agreement as its Undivided Use Interest). For the avoidance of doubt, there shall be no conditions precedent to the CP Satisfaction Date with respect to Timber Road III and Timber Road IV, and such CP Satisfaction Date shall be deemed to have occurred on the Commissioning Date with respect to the Timber Road III Facility and Timber Road IV Facility. Each Co-Owners Proportionate Share in its Shared Assets Group is set forth on Exhibit C, which may be revised from time to time in accordance with this Agreement.

4.2.1 Transmission Line. Each Co-Owner of a Transmission Line shall be entitled to use its Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line. In the event that the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line exceeds the capability provided in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, with Transmission Owners and Transmission Providers consent and approval, each Co-Owners Undivided Use Interest will be increased pro rata in accordance with its Ownership Interest for so long as the Delivery Capability is in excess of the capability provided in the Interconnection Agreements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Co-Owners will not exceed the Maximum Facility Output, as defined in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, unless all necessary approvals and consents are obtained (including from Transmission Owner and Transmission Provider).
4.2.2 Excess Capability. No Co-Owner shall have the right to use more than its Proportionate Share of the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line or portion of the Transmission Line. During periods in which a Co-Owner is not utilizing its full Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line or portion of Transmission Line, the other Co-Owner may utilize more than its full Undivided Use Interest, subject to the operating limits of the Shared Facilities, so long as such usage does not interfere with or adversely affect the first Co-Owners energy schedules and deliveries; and provided that (i) prior to any Co-Owner using more than its Proportionate Share of the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line or portion of the Transmission Line, the Co-Owners shall have obtained all necessary Governmental Authorizations, including FERC acceptance for filing of an effective transmission services agreement for such usage to the extent required and (ii) no payment obligation will attach to such utilization by a Co-Owner of more than its full Undivided Use Interest.
4.2.3 Conditions Precedent. The CP Satisfaction Date with respect to a Co-Owner and the applicable Shared Assets shall be the date on which all of the following have occurred, subject the written consent of the other Co-Owners: (a) sixty (60) calendar days have elapsed since the Co-Owner was granted a final order from FERC pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, as amended, authorizing the sale at wholesale of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services at market based rates, accepting a tariff providing for such sales and granting such waivers and blanket authorizations as are customarily granted by FERC, (b) the Ownership Interest Acquisition shall have occurred as to the applicable Co-Owner in accordance with this Agreement and all Applicable Law, (c) this Agreement shall have been amended to contemplate such Co-Owners applicable Undivided Use Interest on Exhibit B and Exhibit C, as applicable in accordance with this Agreement, (d) the Co-Owners shall have reconciled their sharing of costs incurred for the applicable Shared Assets Group and the relevant Co-Owners have been reimbursed, in each case, as provided in Section 4.3 and (e) no Event of Default shall have occurred and be continuing with respect to such Co-Owner. For the avoidance of doubt, there shall be no conditions precedent to the CP Satisfaction Date with respect to Timber Road III and Timber Road IV, and such CP Satisfaction Date shall be deemed to have occurred on the Commissioning Date with respect to the Timber Road III Facility and Timber Road IV Facility.
4.3 Reimbursement of Capital Costs. To compensate the other Co-Owners in each respective Shared Assets Group for having borne a disproportionate share of the costs and expenses of design, procurement, construction, installation and/or startup of the applicable assets in the respective Shared Assets Group, the following reimbursements have been made or shall be made based on the book value or the estimated value agreed upon by the applicable Co-Owners as of the end of the most recent month prior to the date the reimbursement payment is made on or before the Commissioning Date of the applicable Connecting Facilities, the Co-Owners of such Shared Facilities shall have reconciled their

sharing of costs incurred for the design, procurement, construction, installation and startup of the applicable Shared Assets Group in accordance with their respective Ownership Interests.
4.4 Additional Phases. Subject to the written consent of each other Co-Owner and the terms of this Agreement, including as otherwise set forth in this Article IV, a Co-Owner or its Affiliate, shall have the right to build and operate an additional phase or phases (an Additional Phase), to connect such Additional Phase (or such portion of the Additional Phase as may be compatible with Transmission Owners interconnection facilities), to the Shared Facilities and to use the Shared Assets, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. The owner of such Additional Phase shall execute a joinder, the form of which is attached as Exhibit E hereto (the Joinder). Notwithstanding anything contained herein to the contrary, the owner of the Additional Phase shall bear any incremental costs and expenses of modifying and upgrading the applicable existing Shared Facilities to accommodate the connection of its Facility.
4.5 Initial Connection to Shared Facilities.
4.5.1 In connection with the initial interconnection of any Facility (a Connecting Facility) to any of the Shared Facilities, the Co-Owner that owns such Connecting Facility (the Connecting Co-Owner) shall be responsible for (and for all initial costs in respect of) the initial interconnection of such Connecting Facility to the Shared Facilities (the New Connection). Each Connecting Co-Owner acknowledges and agrees that the New Connection may result in (a) damage to the Shared Facilities or any other Co-Owners Facility, (b) claims from third parties, and (c) lost revenues associated with scheduled and/or unscheduled outages and/or curtailment of some or all of the energy production from the New Connection of the Connecting Facility to any other Co-Owners Facility (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits, grossed up based on the actual federal income tax rate applicable to the applicable Co-Owner, penalties imposed on the applicable Co-Owner or damages payable by the applicable Co-Owner to a power purchaser, energy hedge provider or transmission service provider for the applicable Co-Owners Facility) (together with related costs and/or expenses, collectively, New Connection Losses).
4.5.2 The Co-Owners hereby agree and acknowledge that the Connecting Co-Owner shall only be responsible for New Connection Losses that are greater than or equal to FIFTY THOUSAND DOLLARS AND 00/100 ($50,000.00) in the aggregate for the New Connection (the New Connection Losses Threshold), and that the Connecting Co-Owner shall have no liability for any New Connection Losses until such New Connection Losses are equal to or greater than the New Connection Losses Threshold.
4.5.3 Subject to Section 4.5.2 above, all New Connection Losses shall be the sole responsibility of the Connecting Co-Owner that owns the applicable Connecting Facility. As part of the process for implementation of any New Connection, the applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall establish a protocol to reasonably minimize disruptions to the Shared Facilities and any other Co-Owners Facility. Within ten (10) Business Days after receipt of written notice from the applicable Connecting Co-Owner that the applicable New Connection has been completed, each of the other Co-Owners shall reasonably determine its actual New Connection Losses and deliver reasonable backup documentation supporting the calculation thereof to the applicable Connecting Co-Owner. Any dispute regarding the calculation of New Connection Losses shall be determined in accordance with the dispute resolution provisions in Exhibit D. The applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall pay to each other Co-Owner all undisputed New 7 Docusign Envelope ID: 988EE8BB-EF10-4F66-9234-03A65094CA0E
Connection Losses incurred by such Co-Owner within thirty (30) days following receipt of the calculation of the New Connection Losses from such Co-Owner. Any disputed New Connection Losses incurred by any Co-Owner that are determined (in accordance with the dispute resolution provisions in Exhibit D) to be owed by the applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall be payable by such Connecting Co-Owner to such other Co-Owner within thirty (30) days following such determination. Each Co-Owner shall have all other rights and remedies as may be provided in this Agreement or otherwise available at law or in equity resulting from any Connecting Co-Owners failure to pay any New Connection Losses.
ARTICLE V -- METERING, MEASUREMENT OF ENERGY DELIVERIES AND LOSSES
5.1 Measurement of Energy and Allocation of Losses. Energy transmitted on the applicable Transmission Line shall be measured and allocated between the Co-Owners of the Shared Facilities as set forth on the Timber Road III / IV / Solar III / Storage III Revenue Metering Diagram. The Timber Road III / IV / Solar III / Storage III Revenue Metering Diagram depicts and delineates several metering connections used to measure energy and allocate losses by and among the Facilities, and such metering calculations are used to determine the Facilities generated real power delivered to and received from the point of interconnect.
5.2 Testing and Repair of Co-Owners Meters.
5.2.1 Inspection and Testing. If applicable and in conformance with the applicable Interconnection Agreement(s), a Co-Owner will cause meters (other than revenue meters owned by the interconnection provider and check meters owned by the individual Co-Owner) to be inspected and tested upon its installation and at least once every twenty four (24) months thereafter and at any other reasonable time upon the other Co-Owners request, which may not be made more than three times in said twenty four (24) month period. The Co-Owner requesting such inspection and testing will pay the costs of same, unless the results of the test show the Co-Owners meter to be inaccurate by more than half of one percent (0.5%), in which case the Co-Owners will share the costs of the test. Each Co-Owner will give the other Co-Owners reasonable advance notice of tests of its meter and the other Co-Owners have the right to witness such tests.
5.2.2 Calibration or Repair. If a test shows a Co-Owners meter to be inaccurate, the owner or owners of the meter will use reasonable efforts to cause its meter to be calibrated, repaired or replaced.
ARTICLE VI -- OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES.
6.1 Engagement of Operator. The Co-Owners hereby engage the Operator to manage, operate, maintain and repair the Shared Facilities and to perform other duties pertaining to the Shared Assets (the O&M Services), all as set forth in this Agreement. The Operator accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof. Co-Owners acknowledge and agree that EDP Renewables North America LLC provides certain services with respect to the NERC Reliability Standards on their behalf and is the registered entity.
6.2 Standards for Operators Performance. Operator shall perform or cause to performed the O&M Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the Material Project Agreements, the Shared 8 Docusign Envelope ID: 988EE8BB-EF10-4F66-9234-03A65094CA0E
Real Property Agreements, this Agreement and all Applicable Laws and requirements of Governmental Authorities, including without limitation all Hazardous Materials Laws and all Environmental Laws, and all safety policies and procedures (collectively, the Performance Standard).
6.3 O&M Services. The Operator shall provide or cause to be provided the following services on behalf of each of the Co-Owners who have an Undivided Use Interest from and after the date such Co-Owner has notified Operator of its exercised right to an Undivided Use Interest in the Shared Assets pursuant to Section 4.2 (the O&M Services Commencement Date):
(a) Manage, supervise, operate, repair and maintain the Shared Assets, including the day to day management of the Shared Assets in accordance with Material Project Agreements¸ and in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the Annual O&M Budget;
(b) pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Assets including but not limited to taxes and assessments pursuant to Section 12.2, and maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Operator in connection with its duties herein shall be maintained;
(c) expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities;
(d) notify every Co-Owner of any notice (or any other information reasonably anticipated to affect the Co-Owners) received by the Operator or received from any Co-Owner;
(e) manage compliance with the Co-Owners rights in Shared Real Property in accordance with the Shared Real Property Agreements, including making payments required thereunder; provided that the Operator shall have no right to amend such rights in the Shared Real Property; and
(f) with respect to the Shared Real Property and the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Real Property, oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the use, operation or ownership of the Shared Real Property or the Shared Facilities locate on the Shared Real Property.
6.4 Scheduled Maintenance. Operator shall schedule, or cause to be scheduled, maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities so as to minimize interference with Co-Owners scheduled energy deliveries. Maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities shall be scheduled, to the maximum extent possible, during scheduled maintenance outages of the Co-Owners Facilities. Each Co-Owner will provide to the Operator and the other affected Co-Owners by January 1 of each year a schedule of planned maintenance outages on such Co-Owners Facility for the subsequent twelve- month period. Scheduled outages of the Shared Facilities will be subject to the mutual approval by the affected Co-Owners, such approval not to be unreasonably withheld. Operator will seek to limit the duration of any outage, planned or unplanned, consistent with Good Utility Practice.
6.5 Unplanned Outages. Operator will notify, or cause to be notified, Co-Owners of all emergency or unplanned outages of any of the Shared Facilities as soon as practicable, in accordance

with Good Utility Practice, and will provide an estimated time of return of the Shared Facilities to service, or if not known, will keep, or cause to be kept, Co-Owners advised regarding the status of same.
6.6 Emergency Conditions. In the event of a condition involving the Shared Assets that could be reasonably expected by Operator to result in possible personal injury, loss of life, damage to or destruction of property, or danger to the public (an Emergency Condition), the Operator shall, without the need for prior notification of the Co-Owners, take such action, or cause such action, as may be reasonable and necessary, as determined in the sole discretion of the Operator, to prevent, avoid or mitigate such loss, and shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, report any such emergency, including the Operators response thereto, to the Co-Owners, and Operator, if allowed by law, shall be compensated by the Co-Owners for the costs of taking such actions in proportion to their Ownership Interest in the Shared Assets so affected.
6.7 O&M Costs. Costs of performing O&M Services (the O&M Costs) shall be budgeted accordingly and include all payments made and expenses incurred by Operator in performing O&M Services (at cost and without markup), including but not limited to related overheads and applicable taxes, and costs (except insurance costs) related to ownership of the Shared Assets.
6.8 Budgeting Process. Each year during the term of this Agreement, Operator will prepare a forecast budget of O&M Costs for the following calendar year and will provide a copy to Co-Owners by December 1st. Co-Owners will have ten (10) days thereafter to review the forecast budget and discuss any concerns with the forecast budget with Operator, provided that following the 10-day period such forecast budget of O&M Costs shall be deemed approved if no concerns are identified in writing by the Co-Owners. Operators implementation of the O&M Services consistent with the forecast budget is subject to Co-Owners prior approval, not to be unreasonably withheld (such approved forecast budget, the Annual O&M Budget)
6.9 Extraordinary Maintenance. Each Co-Owner agrees to reimburse Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of the costs of any maintenance or other services required in the event of unusual or catastrophic circumstances, to the extent such costs were not included in the forecast budget for O&M Services and incurred by the Operator (Extraordinary Maintenance).
6.10 Responsibility for O&M Costs. Each Co-Owner shall be responsible for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of O&M Costs, including its share of the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance incurred by Operator, which shall be invoiced by Operator on a quarterly basis. On or before the tenth (10th) day following the end of each calendar quarter, Operator shall invoice Co-Owners for their respective Undivided Use Interest of 1/4 of the amount of the current Annual O&M Budget, along with the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance performed in the previous quarter. The invoices shall be delivered to the parties identified in Section 17.15. Co-Owners shall pay such invoice within thirty (30) days of its receipt (the Due Date). Any amounts not paid by the Due Date shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the then-effective prime rate of interest published under Money Rates by The Wall Street Journal, plus two percent per annum from the Due Date to the date of payment (the Late Payment Rate). For purposes of this Section 6.10 and for Section 6.11, receipt shall mean the date upon which the invoice is received in accordance with Section 17.15. In the event that any Due Date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such payment shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter.

6.11 Disputes. If a Co-Owner disputes the accuracy of all or any portion of an invoice, such Co-Owner shall, nevertheless, pay the undisputed portion of the amount owing on the invoice and submit to Operator a written statement detailing the items and amount disputed. If Co-Owner and Operator are unable to resolve the disputed items, the matter will be resolved in accordance with the dispute resolution provisions in Exhibit D. If Co-Owner prevails with respect to the disputed amounts, Operator shall refund Co-Owner the disputed amounts, including interest on the disputed amounts at the Late Payment Rate.
6.12 No Waiver of Right to Audit. Any payment made by a Co-Owner pursuant to this Agreement shall not constitute a waiver of any right of such Co-Owner to question or contest the accuracy of any charge, or to request and receive from Operator sufficient data to audit any charge concerning which a Co-Owner has a question or which is or may be contested, provided, however, that Co-Owner must initiate any audit or data request no later than twelve (12) months after the Due Date of any such bill or charge and bear reasonable costs associated with such audit, and provided further that if as a result of the audit a determination is made that errors were made by Operator, Operator shall, in addition to correcting the error, reimburse the costs of the audit to the Co-Owners.
6.13 Obligations. The Operator shall have no liability for any obligations except those expressly stated in this Agreement, and nothing in this Agreement shall obligate the Operator to perform any duties or assume any liabilities under any agreement to which the Operator is not directly a party unless such duties are also expressly stated in this Agreement, and then only to such extent. The Co- Owners acknowledge that the Operators performance under this Agreement is dependent upon the Co- Owners having complied with their obligations under this Agreement and the Operator having timely and appropriate access to all parts of the Shared Assets and access to all documents as reasonably required by the Operator.
ARTICLE VII -- DAMAGE OR DESTRUCTION OF SHARED FACILITIES
7.1 Damage or Destruction. In the event of any damage or destruction to or other failure of all or any part of the Shared Facilities that affects the business operations of one or more Co-Owners in a Shared Assets Group (each an Affected Party), such Affected Party shall, subject to any contrary requirements set forth in Material Project Agreements or by Applicable Law, take all commercially reasonable actions as may be necessary or appropriate to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities in order to restore the affected Shared Facilities to substantially the same condition (or better) as before such damage or destruction (and any costs associated with such actions, after accounting for recoveries under any applicable insurance policies, will be shared by the Co-Owners pro rata based on their Ownership Interests, as applicable). Following any such damage, destruction or failure, if (i) the Affected Party fails to diligently proceed with the repair or replacement of the affected Shared Facilities in accordance with the preceding sentence or (ii) the Affected Party notifies the other affected Co-Owners that it does not intend to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities, then in either such case, the other affected Co-Owners shall have the right to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities (or a portion thereof sufficient to serve such other Co-Owners requirements) and continue the operation and maintenance thereof for the remainder of the Term; provided, that in such event, the Affected Party shall be obligated to the Co-Owners funding the repair or replacement of the Shared Facilities to the extent of its Proportionate Share of the costs of repair or replacement; and provided further, that such other Co- Owners shall not unreasonably interfere with the business operations of the Affected Party. In all events, the Co-Owners shall cooperate with each other in good faith to minimize the impact thereof on the Co- Owners and their respective business operations. 11 Docusign Envelope ID: 988EE8BB-EF10-4F66-9234-03A65094CA0E
ARTICLE VIII -- CESSATION OF OPERATIONS BY A CO-OWNER
8.1 Co-Owner Ceasing Operations. DISPUTE RESOLUTION PROCEDURES
1. Consideration by the Authorized Representatives.
All questions concerning interpretation of this Agreement, the acceptable fulfillment of the Co-Owners respective obligations hereunder, as well as all other questions regarding this Agreement in each case that cannot readily be resolved by the Co-Owners shall be resolved in accordance with this Exhibit D. In the event that the authorized representatives of the Co-Owners cannot reach agreement on any question arising under this Agreement, such dispute shall be referred to senior officers of the Co-Owners pursuant to Paragraph 2 below.
2. Negotiations by Senior Officers.
Any disputes arising pursuant to this Agreement that cannot be resolved by the authorized representatives of the Co-Owners within fourteen (14) days after receipt of notice of such dispute (specifically referencing this Exhibit D) shall be referred to the vice president or other senior officer of each of the Co-Owners having executive responsibility for such Co-Owners Facility. If such senior officers, negotiating in good faith, fail to reach an agreement within a reasonable period of time, not exceeding twenty (20) days after such referral, then any Co-Owner to such dispute may institute proceedings as set forth in Paragraph 3 below.
3. Formal Dispute Resolution.
(a) If a dispute described in Paragraph 2 is not resolved by the executive management of the Co-Owners, the Co-Owners shall engage in non-binding mediation of such dispute. Such mediation shall be conducted (i) in Houston, Texas, (ii) within thirty (30) days of a Co-Owner instituting dispute resolution under this Paragraph 3, (iii) by a single, impartial mediator who is selected by the mutual agreement of the Co-Owners, and (iv) in accordance with such procedures as may be adopted by such mediator. Such mediation shall not, without the express agreement of the Co-Owners at the time, extend for a period of more than two (2) days. Each Co-Owner may be represented by persons of such Co-Owners choice during such mediation. Nothing herein shall be deemed to grant any mediator the authority to impose a resolution of any dispute being mediated. Any information introduced, proposals made or positions taken in the mediation shall be deemed to be confidential and for settlement purposes only and may not be introduced by the other Co-Owner in any subsequent litigation of the matters subject to mediation. The Co- Owners shall share the costs of the mediator, including any fees and meeting room rentals.
(b) If a dispute described in Paragraph 2 is not resolved by the executive management of the Co-Owners and the Co-Owners have not otherwise resolved such dispute through mediation pursuant to Paragraph 3(a), a Co-Owner may submit the matter at issue for resolution in an action brought before the courts of the State of Ohio in the County of Paulding or in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Ohio, which courts shall have nonexclusive jurisdiction with respect to such matters.
